{"title_page": "West Virginia & Regional History Center", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=October 2010}}\n{{primary sources|date=January 2016}}\n}}\n\n[[Image:WVRHClogo.png|right|150px]]\nThe '''West Virginia & Regional History Center''' (WVRHC),<ref name =\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web|title=WVU Libraries Rename WVRHC|url=http://www.libraries.wvu.edu/about/news/2013/04/05/wvu-libraries-renames-wvrhc/|accessdate=2013-07-15}}</ref>  is the largest archival collection housing documents and manuscripts involving [[West Virginia]] and the surrounding central Appalachian region.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Maxwell|first1=Monte|title=WVU Libraries renames its West Virginia and regional history area|url=http://wvutoday.wvu.edu/n/2013/04/16/wvu-libraries-renames-its-west-virginia-and-regional-history-area|accessdate=24 October 2016|publisher=WVUToday|date=16 April 2013}}</ref>  Because of name changes over the years, it is sometimes referred to as the \"West Virginia Collection.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=WV & Regional History Center|url=https://mainstreetmorgantown.wordpress.com/west-virginia-and-regional-history-center/|website=Mainstreet Morgantown|date=5 June 2014|accessdate=2016-10-24}}</ref> The WVRHC is the Special Collections division of the [[West Virginia University Libraries|WVU Libraries]].  According to the University, the Center holds over 36,000 linear feet of manuscripts, 100,000 books, 100,000 pamphlets, 1,200 [[newspaper]] titles, over 1 million [[photographs]] and prints, 5,000 maps, and 40,000 [[microfilm]]s, as well as [[oral histories]], films and [[folk music]] recordings. Through donations, the WVRHC provides access to and preserves information on the history and cultural aspects of West Virginia and the central [[Appalachian Region]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Collection to Collections State By State|url=https://www.imls.gov/assets/1/AssetManager/C2C_WV.pdf|website=Institute of Museum and Library Services}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=West Virginia and Regional History Center|url=https://mainstreetmorgantown.wordpress.com/west-virginia-and-regional-history-center/|website=Main Street Morgantown|date=5 June 2014|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{History of West Virginia}}\nThe Center was created in the 1920s when WVU history professor Charles Ambler began to actively seek support for the preservation of state historical records and resources.  In 1930 the University set aside space for storage and offices to support the Center's first manuscript acquisition, the \"''Waitman Willey Papers''\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Maxwell|first1=Monte|title=WVU Libraries renames its West Virginia and regional history area|url=http://wvutoday.wvu.edu/n/2013/04/16/wvu-libraries-renames-its-west-virginia-and-regional-history-area|accessdate=24 October 2016|publisher=WVUToday|date=16 April 2013}}</ref> [[Waitman T. Willey|Waitman Willey]] was an early Senator for West Virginia and the man who proposed the formation of the state on May 29, 1862 to the [[United States Senate]]. Throughout 1931, Ambler traveled through West Virginia and inventoried hundreds of small local manuscript collections stored in attics and churches across the state.  Among the collections located, many were donated to the university including the papers of [[Henry Gassaway Davis]], [[Francis H. Pierpont]], and [[Johnson Newlon Camden]], all key political figures in West Virginia history.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Maxwell|first1=Monte|title=WVU Libraries renames its West Virginia and regional history area|url=http://wvutoday.wvu.edu/n/2013/04/16/wvu-libraries-renames-its-west-virginia-and-regional-history-area|accessdate=24 October 2016|publisher=WVUToday|date=16 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=West Virginia and Regional History Center|url=https://mainstreetmorgantown.wordpress.com/west-virginia-and-regional-history-center/|website=Main Street Morgantown|date=5 June 2014|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1933, the growing \"Division of Documents,\" as the collection was known at the time, was formally authorized by the WVU Board of Governors.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Maxwell|first1=Monte|title=WVU Libraries renames its West Virginia and regional history area|url=http://wvutoday.wvu.edu/n/2013/04/16/wvu-libraries-renames-its-west-virginia-and-regional-history-area|accessdate=24 October 2016|publisher=WVUToday|date=16 April 2013}}</ref> An act of the West Virginia Legislature declared the collection an official depository for state government records in 1934.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Maxwell|first1=Monte|title=WVU Libraries renames its West Virginia and regional history area|url=http://wvutoday.wvu.edu/n/2013/04/16/wvu-libraries-renames-its-west-virginia-and-regional-history-area|accessdate=24 October 2016|publisher=WVUToday|date=16 April 2013}}</ref> Eventually, with the addition of [[Monongalia County, West Virginia|Monongalia]] and [[Ohio County, West Virginia|Ohio County]] records, as well as numerous city records from throughout West Virginia, the Center began to grow rapidly.  It advanced again with the acquisition of the papers of Governor [[Arthur I. Boreman]] and several of his successors. Money provided by [[President of the United States|President]] [[Franklin Roosevelt]]'s [[Works Progress Administration]], the first archival assistants were hired and in 1935 the first full-time archivist was hired.\n\nIn the 1940s and 1950s, the WVRHC continued to grow with photographs, rare books, periodicals, and [[multimedia]] being added.  An active collecting program resulted in the Center growing from 375 holdings in the 1930s to over 1,500 by 1970.  It doubled again by 1990 and continues to grow as West Virginia's leading historical reference center.\n\nThe WVRHC covers all aspects of West Virginia history, including the formation of the state during the [[American Civil War]], its political development, and its economic and industrial heritage.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mazzella|first1=Diana|title=Unearthed at WVU Libraries: Stories you've never been told from West Virginia's attic|url=http://www.fayettetribune.com/news/local_news/unearthed-at-wvu-libraries-stories-you-ve-never-been-told/article_6de6fa1d-7f0b-568d-a275-ec266d7e1ed9.html|accessdate=24 October 2016|publisher=The Fayette Tribune|date=29 July 2013}}</ref> Contained in its Civil War collection are numerous journals from soldiers, personal papers from many of the states early politicians, and two rare 35-star [[American Flag]]s, one of which hangs in the entrance to the Center. Immediately after the birth of West Virginia as the nation's thirty-fifty state in 1863, Union forces returning from the Battle of Gettysburg raised this flag over Sheperdstown.<ref>https://wvrhc.lib.wvu.edu/news/newsletter/1985-1994/v1n2.pdf</ref> The WVHRC collection also includes a variety of artifacts and texts not directly related to West Virginia, including 600 works and pieces of memorabilia from [[Isaac Asimov]], original folio editions of [[William Shakespeare's]] collected plays, and the journal of an officer from the all African American [[54th Massachusetts Infantry Regiment]] that fought in the Civil War.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mazzella|first1=Diana|title=Unearthed at WVU Libraries: Stories you've never been told from West Virginia's attic|url=http://www.fayettetribune.com/news/local_news/unearthed-at-wvu-libraries-stories-you-ve-never-been-told/article_6de6fa1d-7f0b-568d-a275-ec266d7e1ed9.html|accessdate=24 October 2016|publisher=The Fayette Tribune|date=29 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Collections ==\n*[[Jay Rockefeller]]\n*[[Arch A. Moore Jr.|Arch A. Moore, Jr.]] \n*[[Pearl S. Buck]]\n*[[Isaac Asimov]]\n*[[Storer College]]\n*[[Clarysville, Maryland]]\n*[[David Hunter Strother|Drawings of David Hunter Strother]]\n*[https://holt.lib.wvu.edu/ Rush Dew Holt Political Cartoons]\n*[https://lib.wvu.edu/collections/collection.php?id=47 Rare Books]\n*[https://civilwarwv.lib.wvu.edu/ Pierpont Civil War Telegrams]\n*[https://images.lib.wvu.edu/p/pec/ Printed Ephemera Collection]\n*[[Emory Kemp]]\n*[[Ancella Radford Bickley]]\n\n==West Virginia History OnView==\nThe West Virginia and Regional History Center has been engaged in a digitization project since 2004, and has digitized over 52,000 historical photographs from its broad and deep holdings as of 2017.<ref name =\"The Fayette Tribune\">{{cite web|title=Unearthed at WVU Libraries: Stories you've never been told from West Virginia's attic|url=http://www.fayettetribune.com/news/local_news/unearthed-at-wvu-libraries-stories-you-ve-never-been-told/article_6de6fa1d-7f0b-568d-a275-ec266d7e1ed9.html|website=The Fayette Tribune|accessdate=2013-06-29}}</ref> The Center's photographs archives contain over a million photographs, and more are being digitized each day. The digital archive is the largest collection of West Virginia and Appalachian photography accessible online, and draws more than half a million visitors to the WVRHC website annually, accounting for more than a third of all traffic on WVU Libraries' website.\n\n== West Virginia Day ==\nThe West Virginia and Regional History Center participates in the yearly [[West Virginia Day]] Event.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Huddock|first1=Megan|title=Reception Held to Celebrate West Virginia Day and 150th Anniversary of Storer College|url=http://www.wvalways.com/story/29357977/reception-held-to-celebrate-west-virginia-day-and-150th-anniversary-of-storer-college|accessdate=24 October 2016|publisher=WBOY Channel 12 Clarksburg|date=5 October 2015}}</ref> WVRHC takes part in hosting a reception and showcasing various aspects of the center's collection during this time. The theme is different every year. Depending on the collection, the reception includes: speakers, panels, book signing, readings, and viewings.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://wvrhc.lib.wvu.edu/ West Virginia and Regional History Center website]\n*[http://wvhistoryonview.org/ West Virginia History OnView database]\n*[https://rockefeller.lib.wvu.edu/ Jay Rockefeller Collection]\n*[https://moore.lib.wvu.edu/ Arch A. Moore, Jr. & Shelley Moore Collection]\n*[https://pearlsbuck.lib.wvu.edu/ Storer College Collection]\n*[https://clarysville.lib.wvu.edu/ Clarysville, Maryland Collection]\n*[https://images.lib.wvu.edu/s/strother/ Drawings of David Hunter Strother]\n*[http://www.libraries.wvu.edu/about/news/2000/09/15/west-virginia-collection-holds-keys-to-the-states-history/ WV Collection holds Keys to the State's History] - article about the Center and its history\n\n{{coord|39|37|59.5|N|79|57|15.8|W|type:landmark_region:US-WV|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:West Virginia And Regional History Collection}}\n[[Category:West Virginia University]]\n[[Category:History of West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Monongalia County, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:University and college academic libraries in the United States|West Virginia University]]\n[[Category:Works Progress Administration in West Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=October 2010}}\n{{primary sources|date=January 2016}}\n[[Image:WVRHClogo.png|right|150px]]\nThe '''West Virginia & Regional History Center''' (WVRHC),<ref name =\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web|title=WVU Libraries Rename WVRHC|url=http://www.libraries.wvu.edu/about/news/2013/04/05/wvu-libraries-renames-wvrhc/|accessdate=2013-07-15}}</ref>  is the largest archival collection housing documents and manuscripts involving [[West Virginia]] and the surrounding central Appalachian region.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Maxwell|first1=Monte|title=WVU Libraries renames its West Virginia and regional history area|url=http://wvutoday.wvu.edu/n/2013/04/16/wvu-libraries-renames-its-west-virginia-and-regional-history-area|accessdate=24 October 2016|publisher=WVUToday|date=16 April 2013}}</ref>  Because of name changes over the years, it is sometimes referred to as the \"West Virginia Collection.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=WV & Regional History Center|url=https://mainstreetmorgantown.wordpress.com/west-virginia-and-regional-history-center/|website=Mainstreet Morgantown|date=5 June 2014|accessdate=2016-10-24}}</ref> The WVRHC is the Special Collections division of the [[West Virginia University Libraries|WVU Libraries]].  According to the University, the Center holds over 36,000 linear feet of manuscripts, 100,000 books, 100,000 pamphlets, 1,200 [[newspaper]] titles, over 1 million [[photographs]] and prints, 5,000 maps, and 40,000 [[microfilm]]s, as well as [[oral histories]], films and [[folk music]] recordings. Through donations, the WVRHC provides access to and preserves information on the history and cultural aspects of West Virginia and the central [[Appalachian Region]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Collection to Collections State By State|url=https://www.imls.gov/assets/1/AssetManager/C2C_WV.pdf|website=Institute of Museum and Library Services}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=West Virginia and Regional History Center|url=https://mainstreetmorgantown.wordpress.com/west-virginia-and-regional-history-center/|website=Main Street Morgantown|date=5 June 2014|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{History of West Virginia}}\nThe Center was created in the 1920s when WVU history professor Charles Ambler began to actively seek support for the preservation of state historical records and resources.  In 1930 the University set aside space for storage and offices to support the Center's first manuscript acquisition, the \"''Waitman Willey Papers''\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Maxwell|first1=Monte|title=WVU Libraries renames its West Virginia and regional history area|url=http://wvutoday.wvu.edu/n/2013/04/16/wvu-libraries-renames-its-west-virginia-and-regional-history-area|accessdate=24 October 2016|publisher=WVUToday|date=16 April 2013}}</ref> [[Waitman T. Willey|Waitman Willey]] was an early Senator for West Virginia and the man who proposed the formation of the state on May 29, 1862 to the [[United States Senate]]. Throughout 1931, Ambler traveled through West Virginia and inventoried hundreds of small local manuscript collections stored in attics and churches across the state.  Among the collections located, many were donated to the university including the papers of [[Henry Gassaway Davis]], [[Francis H. Pierpont]], and [[Johnson Newlon Camden]], all key political figures in West Virginia history.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Maxwell|first1=Monte|title=WVU Libraries renames its West Virginia and regional history area|url=http://wvutoday.wvu.edu/n/2013/04/16/wvu-libraries-renames-its-west-virginia-and-regional-history-area|accessdate=24 October 2016|publisher=WVUToday|date=16 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=West Virginia and Regional History Center|url=https://mainstreetmorgantown.wordpress.com/west-virginia-and-regional-history-center/|website=Main Street Morgantown|date=5 June 2014|accessdate=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1933, the growing \"Division of Documents,\" as the collection was known at the time, was formally authorized by the WVU Board of Governors.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Maxwell|first1=Monte|title=WVU Libraries renames its West Virginia and regional history area|url=http://wvutoday.wvu.edu/n/2013/04/16/wvu-libraries-renames-its-west-virginia-and-regional-history-area|accessdate=24 October 2016|publisher=WVUToday|date=16 April 2013}}</ref> An act of the West Virginia Legislature declared the collection an official depository for state government records in 1934.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Maxwell|first1=Monte|title=WVU Libraries renames its West Virginia and regional history area|url=http://wvutoday.wvu.edu/n/2013/04/16/wvu-libraries-renames-its-west-virginia-and-regional-history-area|accessdate=24 October 2016|publisher=WVUToday|date=16 April 2013}}</ref> Eventually, with the addition of [[Monongalia County, West Virginia|Monongalia]] and [[Ohio County, West Virginia|Ohio County]] records, as well as numerous city records from throughout West Virginia, the Center began to grow rapidly.  It advanced again with the acquisition of the papers of Governor [[Arthur I. Boreman]] and several of his successors. Money provided by [[President of the United States|President]] [[Franklin Roosevelt]]'s [[Works Progress Administration]], the first archival assistants were hired and in 1935 the first full-time archivist was hired.\n\nIn the 1940s and 1950s, the WVRHC continued to grow with photographs, rare books, periodicals, and [[multimedia]] being added.  An active collecting program resulted in the Center growing from 375 holdings in the 1930s to over 1,500 by 1970.  It doubled again by 1990 and continues to grow as West Virginia's leading historical reference center.\n\nThe WVRHC covers all aspects of West Virginia history, including the formation of the state during the [[American Civil War]], its political development, and its economic and industrial heritage.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mazzella|first1=Diana|title=Unearthed at WVU Libraries: Stories you've never been told from West Virginia's attic|url=http://www.fayettetribune.com/news/local_news/unearthed-at-wvu-libraries-stories-you-ve-never-been-told/article_6de6fa1d-7f0b-568d-a275-ec266d7e1ed9.html|accessdate=24 October 2016|publisher=The Fayette Tribune|date=29 July 2013}}</ref> Contained in its Civil War collection are numerous journals from soldiers, personal papers from many of the states early politicians, and two rare 35-star [[American Flag]]s, one of which hangs in the entrance to the Center. Immediately after the birth of West Virginia as the nation's thirty-fifty state in 1863, Union forces returning from the Battle of Gettysburg raised this flag over Sheperdstown.<ref>https://wvrhc.lib.wvu.edu/news/newsletter/1985-1994/v1n2.pdf</ref> The WVHRC collection also includes a variety of artifacts and texts not directly related to West Virginia, including 600 works and pieces of memorabilia from [[Isaac Asimov]], original folio editions of [[William Shakespeare's]] collected plays, and the journal of an officer from the all African American [[54th Massachusetts Infantry Regiment]] that fought in the Civil War.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mazzella|first1=Diana|title=Unearthed at WVU Libraries: Stories you've never been told from West Virginia's attic|url=http://www.fayettetribune.com/news/local_news/unearthed-at-wvu-libraries-stories-you-ve-never-been-told/article_6de6fa1d-7f0b-568d-a275-ec266d7e1ed9.html|accessdate=24 October 2016|publisher=The Fayette Tribune|date=29 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Collections ==\n*[[Jay Rockefeller]]\n*[[Arch A. Moore Jr.|Arch A. Moore, Jr.]] \n*[[Pearl S. Buck]]\n*[[Isaac Asimov]]\n*[[Storer College]]\n*[[Clarysville, Maryland]]\n*[[David Hunter Strother|Drawings of David Hunter Strother]]\n*[https://holt.lib.wvu.edu/ Rush Dew Holt Political Cartoons]\n*[https://lib.wvu.edu/collections/collection.php?id=47 Rare Books]\n*[https://civilwarwv.lib.wvu.edu/ Pierpont Civil War Telegrams]\n*[https://images.lib.wvu.edu/p/pec/ Printed Ephemera Collection]\n*[[Emory Kemp]]\n*[[Ancella Radford Bickley]]\n\n==West Virginia History OnView==\nThe West Virginia and Regional History Center has been engaged in a digitization project since 2004, and has digitized over 52,000 historical photographs from its broad and deep holdings as of 2017.<ref name =\"The Fayette Tribune\">{{cite web|title=Unearthed at WVU Libraries: Stories you've never been told from West Virginia's attic|url=http://www.fayettetribune.com/news/local_news/unearthed-at-wvu-libraries-stories-you-ve-never-been-told/article_6de6fa1d-7f0b-568d-a275-ec266d7e1ed9.html|website=The Fayette Tribune|accessdate=2013-06-29}}</ref> The Center's photographs archives contain over a million photographs, and more are being digitized each day. The digital archive is the largest collection of West Virginia and Appalachian photography accessible online, and draws more than half a million visitors to the WVRHC website annually, accounting for more than a third of all traffic on WVU Libraries' website.\n\n== West Virginia Day ==\nThe West Virginia and Regional History Center participates in the yearly [[West Virginia Day]] Event.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Huddock|first1=Megan|title=Reception Held to Celebrate West Virginia Day and 150th Anniversary of Storer College|url=http://www.wvalways.com/story/29357977/reception-held-to-celebrate-west-virginia-day-and-150th-anniversary-of-storer-college|accessdate=24 October 2016|publisher=WBOY Channel 12 Clarksburg|date=5 October 2015}}</ref> WVRHC takes part in hosting a reception and showcasing various aspects of the center's collection during this time. The theme is different every year. Depending on the collection, the reception includes: speakers, panels, book signing, readings, and viewings.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://wvrhc.lib.wvu.edu/ West Virginia and Regional History Center website]\n*[http://wvhistoryonview.org/ West Virginia History OnView database]\n*[https://rockefeller.lib.wvu.edu/ Jay Rockefeller Collection]\n*[https://moore.lib.wvu.edu/ Arch A. Moore, Jr. & Shelley Moore Collection]\n*[https://pearlsbuck.lib.wvu.edu/ Storer College Collection]\n*[https://clarysville.lib.wvu.edu/ Clarysville, Maryland Collection]\n*[https://images.lib.wvu.edu/s/strother/ Drawings of David Hunter Strother]\n*[http://www.libraries.wvu.edu/about/news/2000/09/15/west-virginia-collection-holds-keys-to-the-states-history/ WV Collection holds Keys to the State's History] - article about the Center and its history\n\n{{coord|39|37|59.5|N|79|57|15.8|W|type:landmark_region:US-WV|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:West Virginia And Regional History Collection}}\n[[Category:West Virginia University]]\n[[Category:History of West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Monongalia County, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:University and college academic libraries in the United States|West Virginia University]]\n[[Category:Works Progress Administration in West Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao